2026-06-24 17:38:30,676 DEBUG Tool result: ToolCallRecord(
    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_f7fe0c3448bb4a72be807e28',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"In {{spacex_s1}}, what does the filing disclose about satellite useful lives, depreciation policies, satellite replenishment, and the LEO constellation economics? Also, what is the total depreciation and amortization expense for the consolidated entity in FY2025?"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1}}, what does the filing disclose about satellite useful lives, depreciation policies, satellite replenishment, and the LEO constellation economics? Also, what is the total depreciation and amortization expense for the consolidated entity in FY2025?'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Satellite Useful Lives, Depreciation Policies, Replenishment & LEO Economics\n\n## Satellite Useful Lives\n\nThe filing discloses two specific useful-life categories for satellites:\n\n- **Broadband satellites: 5-year useful life**\n- **First-generation mobile satellites: 3-year useful life**\n\nUseful lives are estimated based on **engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, design enhancements across generations, and planned transitions to newer satellite technology**. Management periodically reviews these estimates with engineering and operations teams and revises them as additional data becomes available.\n\nAdditional factors considered for satellite assets include **on-orbit performance, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, and the evolution of constellation density and technology**.\n\n## Depreciation Policies\n\n| Asset Category | Depreciation Method |\n|---|---|\n| General PP&E | Straight-line over estimated useful lives |\n| Flight vehicles & spacecraft | Over expected number of average flights per vehicle |\n| Leasehold improvements | Shorter of useful life or lease term |\n| Maintenance & repairs | Expensed as incurred |\n| Significant refurbishments/enhancements | Capitalized and depreciated ratably over identified useful life |\n\nWhen useful lives or expected remaining flights are shorter or longer than originally estimated, the Company **adjusts the rate of depreciation** to reflect the revised estimates.\n\n## Satellite Replenishment & LEO Constellation Economics\n\nThe filing reveals several economic dynamics of the LEO constellation model:\n\n1. **Short useful lives drive high depreciation burden** — With broadband satellites depreciated over just 5 years, the Connectivity segment faces substantial recurring depreciation as the constellation is continually replenished.\n\n2. **Sensitivity is material** — A one-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would have an approximately **$480 million impact on operating income for FY2025** and **$170 million for Q1 2026**. By contrast, a five-flight change in average remaining flights for flight vehicles/spacecraft would *not* be material — underscoring that satellite useful-life assumptions are far more impactful to earnings than launch vehicle assumptions.\n\n3. **Replenishment cost pressure** — Connectivity cost of revenue increased by **$1,153 million** in 2025, driven by "higher depreciation as the number of satellites placed into orbit grew and higher operating expenses." The filing also cites "depreciation of capitalized launch and satellite costs due to the increase in Starlink flights" as a recurring headwind to Connectivity operating income.\n\n4. **Capitalized launch costs flow through depreciation** — As Starlink satellite launches increased from 89 in 2024 to 122 in 2025, a relatively greater share of launch operations and overhead costs were capitalized into the Connectivity segment, shifting costs from period expense to depreciated asset.\n\n5. **Technology evolution risk** — The Company explicitly considers "planned transitions to newer satellite technology" and "the evolution of constellation density and technology" in setting useful lives, acknowledging that generational obsolescence can shorten economic lives.\n\n## Total Consolidated Depreciation and Amortization — FY2025\n\nTwo figures are disclosed, depending on scope:\n\n| Metric | FY2025 Amount |\n|---|---|\n| **Depreciation expense** (PP&E only) | **$5,915 million** |\n| **Depreciation and amortization** (segment supplemental, includes intangibles) | **$6,701 million** |\n\nThe $6,701 million segment-level D&A breaks down as follows:\n\n| Segment | D&A (FY2025) |\n|---|---|\n| Space | $757 million |\n| Connectivity | $2,376 million |\n| AI | $3,568 million |\n| **Total Reportable Segments** | **$6,701 million** |\n\nThe ~$786 million difference between the two figures ($6,701M − $5,915M) is attributable to **amortization of finite-lived intangible assets** (which had a net carrying value of $1,537 million as of December 31, 2025) and potentially other non-PP&E amortization included in the segment supplemental disclosure.',
