2026-06-24 17:39:29,754 DEBUG Tool result: ToolCallRecord(
    tool_call=ToolCall(
        id='call_cdccf92693ff4d9ead1a3d37',
        call_id=None,
        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt":"In {{viasat_10k_2025}}, what is the satellite depreciation expense for the satellite/space segment? What is the satellite segment revenue? What is the segment operating income (or loss) for the satellite segment? Please provide the exact figures and any reconciliation between segment operating income and EBITDA. Also, what does the filing say about satellite useful lives and depreciation policies?"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{viasat_10k_2025}}, what is the satellite depreciation expense for the satellite/space segment? What is the satellite segment revenue? What is the segment operating income (or loss) for the satellite segment? Please provide the exact figures and any reconciliation between segment operating income and EBITDA. Also, what does the filing say about satellite useful lives and depreciation policies?'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Response to Satellite Segment Inquiry\n\n## Important Clarification: Viasat Does Not Report a Standalone "Satellite/Space Segment"\n\nBased on the filing excerpts provided, Viasat reports **two operating segments only**:\n1. **Communication Services** (which contains the company\'s satellite operations, including aviation, government, maritime, and fixed services)\n2. **Defense and Advanced Technologies**\n\nThere is no separately disclosed "satellite segment" or "space segment." Satellite assets, depreciation, and related revenues are embedded within the **Communication Services segment**. The figures below therefore reflect that segment.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Depreciation Expense (Communication Services Segment — FY2025)\n\n| Fiscal Year Ended March 31, | 2025 | 2024 | 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Communication Services Depreciation | **$988,447 thousand** (~$988.4 million) | $825,788 thousand | $350,954 thousand |\n| Defense and Advanced Technologies Depreciation | $48,020 thousand | $41,853 thousand | $52,701 thousand |\n\nNote: This depreciation line is not broken out between satellites, earth stations, networking equipment, and CPE at the segment level. However, the filing separately discloses CPE carrying values (see below).\n\n### CPE Units (Customer Premises Equipment) — Disclosed Separately Within Property, Equipment and Satellites, Net\n\n| As of March 31, | Total Cost | Accumulated Depreciation | Net Book Value |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 2025 | $526.0 million | $328.0 million | $198.0 million |\n| 2024 | $567.5 million | $267.4 million | $300.1 million |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Communication Services Segment Revenue (FY2025)\n\n| Communication Services Revenue | FY2025 | FY2024 | FY2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Aviation services | $1,048,225 | $864,834 | $346,950 |\n| Government satcom services | $754,552 | $596,826 | $165,897 |\n| Maritime services | $477,968 | $430,090 | $3,362 |\n| Fixed services and other services | $741,601 | $906,762 | $919,440 |\n| **Total services** | $3,022,346 | $2,798,512 | $1,435,649 |\n| Total products | $276,139 | $343,028 | $269,126 |\n| **Total communication services revenues** | **$3,298,485 thousand** (~$3,298.5 million) | $3,141,540 | $1,704,775 |\n\n(All figures in thousands of USD.)\n\n---\n\n## 3. Segment Operating Income (Loss) — Communication Services\n\n| Segment Operating Profit (Loss) | FY2025 | FY2024 | FY2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Communication Services** | **$(50,222) thousand** (~$(50.2) million) | $(817,054) thousand | $(189,402) thousand |\n| Defense and Advanced Technologies | $216,675 | $154,413 | $63,257 |\n| Elimination of intersegment | — | — | — |\n\n### Drivers cited in the MD&A for the FY2025 vs. FY2024 improvement:\n- **Prior-year satellite impairment of ~$905.5 million** (FY2024) did not recur\n- Higher earnings contributions of **$40.7 million** from increased service revenues (Inmarsat Acquisition)\n- **$21.5 million decrease** in IR&D expenses (next-gen consumer broadband)\n- Partially offset by:\n  - **$169.4 million ground network impairment** (EMEA exit, Q4 FY2025)\n  - **$31.5 million increase** in SG&A (full year of Inmarsat vs. 10 months in prior year)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Reconciliation Between Segment Operating Profit and Pre-Tax Income (Not EBITDA)\n\nThe filing does **not** present an explicit EBITDA reconciliation in the chunks provided. Instead, the segment operating profit is reconciled to **Income (loss) from continuing operations before income taxes** through the following items (line items identified in the segment note):\n\n- Segment operating profit (loss) before corporate and amortization of acquired intangible assets\n- Amortization of acquired intangible assets\n- (Loss) gain on extinguishment of debt, net\n- Income (loss) from continuing operations before income taxes\n\nA user wishing to construct an EBITDA proxy would need to add back:\n- Depreciation (Communication Services: $988.4M FY2025)\n- Amortization of acquired intangible assets\n- Interest expense (net)\n- Taxes\n- Impairments ($169.4M FY2025 ground network; $905.5M FY2024 satellite)\n\nHowever, **the filing does not explicitly present this as a defined EBITDA measure** in the excerpts provided.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Satellite Useful Lives and Depreciation Policies\n\n### Estimated Useful Lives (from the property and equipment note)\n\n| Asset Category | Estimated Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| Equipment and software | 3 – 7 years |\n| CPE leased equipment | 4 – 7 years |\n| Furniture and fixtures | 7 years |\n| Leasehold improvements | 2 – 20 years |\n| Buildings | 12 – 38 years |\n| **Satellites** | **7 – 17 years** |\n| **Satellite Ka-band capacity obtained under finance leases** | **7 – 15 years** |\n\n### Capitalization Policy (from Significant Accounting Policies)\n\n> "Satellites and other property and equipment, including internally developed software, are recorded at cost or, in the case of certain satellites and other property acquired, the fair value at the date of acquisition, net of accumulated depreciation."\n\n**Capitalized satellite costs include:**\n- Costs of satellite construction and launch\n- Launch insurance\n- Insurance during the period of in-orbit testing\n- Net present value of performance incentive payments expected to be payable to satellite manufacturers (dependent on continued satisfactory performance)\n- Costs directly associated with monitoring and support of satellite construction\n- Interest costs incurred during the period of satellite construction\n\n**Other capitalized costs:**\n- Earth stations, network operations systems, and other supporting assets — construction costs, including interest, are capitalized as incurred.\n\n### Useful Life Estimation Methodology\n\n> "At the time satellites are placed in commercial service, the Company estimates the useful life of its satellites for depreciation purposes based upon an analysis of each satellite\'s performance against the original manufacturer\'s orbital design life, estimated fuel levels and related consumption rates, as well as historical satellite operating trends."\n\nThe Company **periodically reviews** the remaining estimated useful life of its satellites to determine if revisions are necessary.\n\n### Additions, Maintenance, and Disposals\n\n- **Capitalized:** Additions, major renewals, and betterments — depreciated over the remaining life of the underlying asset.\n- **Expensed:** Maintenance, repairs, and minor renewals and betterments — charged to expense as incurred.\n- **Disposals:** Cost and related accumulated depreciation/amortization are removed; any gain or loss is recognized in operations.\n\n### Satellite Launch Cycle Impacts (from MD&A)\n\nThe filing explicitly warns that new satellite launches (including the ViaSat-3 constellation) create a **cyclical pattern** of:\n- Increased operating costs during ramp-up (depreciation, amortization of capitalized software, earth station connectivity, marketing, customer care, support systems)\n- Increased interest expense once the satellite is in commercial service (interest is no longer capitalized)\n- Capacity constraints on existing satellites in the lead-up to new satellite commercial service\n- Subsequent revenue base expansion and operating cost efficiencies as services scale\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Item | FY2025 Figure |\n|---|---|\n| Communication Services segment revenue | $3,298.5 million |\n| Communication Services depreciation expense | $988.4 million |\n| Communication Services segment operating loss | $(50.2) million |\n| Ground network impairment (FY25, EMEA exit) | $169.4 million |\n| Prior-year satellite impairment (FY24, did not recur) | $905.5 million |\n| Satellite useful life range | 7 – 17 years |\n| Satellite Ka-band finance lease capacity useful life | 7 – 15 years |\n| CPE total cost (3/31/2025) | $526.0 million |\n| CPE accumulated depreciation (3/31/2025) | $328.0 million |\n| Explicit EBITDA reconciliation provided? | **No** — only a reconciliation to pre-tax income from continuing operations |\n\nIf you need a specific EBITDA figure, it would have to be **derived** (not directly disclosed) by adding back depreciation, amortization of acquired intangibles, interest, taxes, and impairments to the segment operating profit or to net loss — but the filing excerpts provided do not present this as a defined non-GAAP measure.',
