        output='## SpaceX Connectivity Segment: Implied D&A Add-Back vs. Viasat Satellite Depreciation — LEO vs. GEO Structural Analysis\n\n### 1. SpaceX Connectivity Segment FY2025 EBITDA Bridge\n\nFrom the SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026), the Connectivity segment reconciliation for the year ended December 31, 2025 is:\n\n| (in $ millions) | Connectivity |\n|---|---|\n| Income from operations (Segment Operating Income) | $4,423 |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | **$2,376** |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | $369 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | $0 |\n| Add: Impairment | $0 |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$7,168** |\n\n**Implied D&A add-back = $7,168 − $4,423 − $369 = $2,376 million**\n\nVerification: $4,423 + $2,376 + $369 = $7,168 ✓\n\nConnectivity segment revenue (FY2025): **$11,387 million** (primarily Starlink).\n\n**SpaceX Connectivity D&A as % of segment revenue = $2,376 / $11,387 = 20.87%**\n\nThe S-1 also discloses that SpaceX depreciates **broadband satellites over a 5-year useful life** and **first-generation mobile satellites over a 3-year useful life**, and that a one-year change in the average useful life of satellite assets would have an approximately **$480 million impact on FY2025 operating income** — confirming that satellite depreciation is the dominant driver of the D&A line.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Viasat Most Recent 10-K (FY2025, fiscal year ended March 31, 2025) — Satellite Depreciation Disclosure\n\n**Important disclosure caveat:** Viasat\'s most recent 10-K does **not** report a standalone "space segment" and does **not** separately disclose a "satellite depreciation" line item. Viasat reports two operating segments — **Communication Services** (which contains all satellite operations) and **Defense and Advanced Technologies**. Satellite depreciation is embedded within total Communication Services depreciation. The question\'s premise that Viasat discloses satellite depreciation as a discrete line item is not supported by the filing; the best available proxy is total Communication Services depreciation.\n\n| (in $ millions) | Viasat Communication Services FY2025 |\n|---|---|\n| Segment revenue | $3,298.5 |\n| Segment depreciation expense (total, all assets) | $988.4 |\n| Segment operating income (loss) | $(50.2) |\n| Satellite useful life range | 7 – 17 years |\n| Satellite Ka-band finance-lease capacity useful life | 7 – 15 years |\n| Satellites in service — gross cost | $3,405.1 |\n| Satellite Ka-band capacity (finance leases) — gross cost | $338.2 |\n| Satellites under construction — gross cost | $2,205.3 |\n\n**Viasat total Communication Services depreciation / segment revenue = $988.4 / $3,298.5 = 29.97%**\n\nBecause Viasat does not break out satellite-specific depreciation, an estimate can be derived from gross satellite cost and the midpoint useful life (~12 years for in-service satellites; ~11 years for Ka-band capacity):\n\n**Estimated satellite-only depreciation ≈ ($3,405.1 + $338.2) / 12 ≈ $312 million**\n\n**Estimated satellite depreciation / Communication Services revenue ≈ $312 / $3,298.5 ≈ 9.46%**\n\n---\n\n### 3. Directional Comparison\n\n| Metric | SpaceX Connectivity (LEO) | Viasat Comm. Services (GEO) |\n|---|---|---|\n| D&A / segment revenue (total) | **20.87%** | **29.97%** (total depreciation, not satellite-only) |\n| Estimated satellite-only depreciation / revenue | ~20.9% (D&A is overwhelmingly satellite-driven) | **~9.46%** (estimated) |\n| Satellite useful life | **5 years** (broadband) / 3 years (mobile) | **7 – 17 years** |\n| Segment operating income | **$4,423M (positive)** | **$(50.2)M (loss)** |\n| Implied segment EBITDA (rough) | $7,168M | ~$938M (loss + depreciation) |\n| EBITDA-to-Operating-Income conversion | **61.7%** ($4,423 / $7,168) | **−5.4%** (negative — operating loss despite positive EBITDA) |\n\n**Key directional findings:**\n\n- **Satellite-specific depreciation intensity is structurally higher for LEO.** SpaceX\'s Connectivity D&A (~20.9% of revenue) is overwhelmingly satellite-driven given the 5-year useful life and continuous replenishment, whereas Viasat\'s estimated satellite-only depreciation is roughly half that (~9.5% of revenue) because GEO satellites are depreciated over 7–17 years. The shorter LEO useful life mechanically doubles (or more) the annual depreciation burden per dollar of in-orbit asset.\n\n- **Viasat\'s *total* segment depreciation is actually higher than SpaceX\'s** (29.97% vs. 20.87%) — but this is driven by Viasat\'s ground infrastructure, earth stations, CPE, and a heavy ViaSat-3 investment cycle, not by satellite depreciation per se. This confirms that the satellite-depreciation component specifically is lower for GEO, even though Viasat\'s overall capital intensity is currently elevated.\n\n- **The EBITDA-to-operating-income conversion gap is dramatically different.** SpaceX converts 61.7% of Segment Adjusted EBITDA into operating income. Viasat\'s Communication Services segment shows a **negative** conversion: a ~$988M depreciation add-back flips a $50M operating loss into roughly $938M of implied EBITDA. The depreciation charge is approximately 20× the segment\'s operating loss.\n\n---\n\n### 4. What This Reveals About LEO vs. GEO Satellite Depreciation Profiles\n\n**LEO constellation economics (SpaceX/Starlink):**\n- **Shorter useful lives (5 years vs. 7–17 years)** produce a structurally higher annual depreciation rate per dollar of in-orbit asset.\n- **Higher satellite counts (thousands vs. a handful)** mean a much larger gross asset base is simultaneously depreciating.\n- **Continuous replenishment** (122 Starlink launches in 2025, up from 89 in 2024) means the depreciation charge is a **permanent, steady-state feature** of the P&L — it never declines because retired satellites are continuously replaced by newly capitalized ones. The S-1 explicitly attributes the $1,153M increase in Connectivity cost of revenue to "higher depreciation as the number of satellites placed into orbit grew."\n- **Useful-life sensitivity is extreme:** a one-year change in satellite useful life swings operating income by ~$480M (FY2025), underscoring that the depreciation assumption is the single most material accounting estimate for LEO operators.\n\n**GEO satellite depreciation profiles (Viasat):**\n- **Longer useful lives (7–17 years)** spread capitalized satellite cost over a much longer period, producing lower annual satellite depreciation per dollar of asset.\n- **Fewer, larger satellites** mean depreciation is **lumpy and cyclical** — it spikes when a new satellite (e.g., ViaSat-3) enters commercial service, then runs off over 7–17 years. Between replacement cycles, depreciation can decline materially.\n- **Impairment risk dominates over depreciation timing:** Viasat\'s recent segment losses were driven by a ~$905.5M satellite impairment (FY2024) and a $169.4M ground network impairment (FY2025), not by steady-state depreciation — a different failure mode than LEO.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Why EBITDA-to-Operating-Income Conversion Is Critical for Evaluating LEO Broadband Operators\n\nThe comparison reveals several structural reasons why EBITDA is a particularly misleading profitability metric for LEO broadband operators as a class:\n\n1. **Perpetual capital intensity is hidden by EBITDA.** Unlike GEO operators — where depreciation eventually runs off between replacement cycles — LEO operators face a **permanent depreciation charge** because the constellation must be continuously replenished. EBITDA adds back depreciation as if it were a non-recurring non-cash item, but for LEO it represents a recurring economic cost (satellites must be rebuilt and relaunched). The $2,376M D&A add-back in SpaceX\'s Connectivity bridge is not a one-time accounting artifact; it is the steady-state cost of maintaining a 5-year-life constellation.\n\n2. **Useful-life assumptions are the dominant value driver.** SpaceX\'s disclosure that a one-year useful-life change moves operating income by ~$480M means that EBITDA — which is invariant to useful-life assumptions — strips out precisely the variable that most determines true LEO profitability. Two LEO operators with identical EBITDA can have vastly different operating incomes depending on whether they assume 4, 5, or 6-year satellite lives.\n\n3. **The EBITDA-to-OI gap is structural, not transitional.** For Viasat, the gap between positive EBITDA and negative operating income reflects a combination of cyclical factors (impairments, investment ramp) that may eventually reverse. For LEO operators, the gap is **structural and permanent** — it will persist as long as the constellation is being replenished, because depreciation will always approximate the cost of replacing the retiring fleet.\n\n4. **Scale and cost efficiency determine whether the structural gap is survivable.** SpaceX\'s ability to generate $4,423M of positive Connectivity operating income despite a 20.87% D&A-to-revenue ratio demonstrates that LEO economics can work — but only when (a) revenue scales faster than the depreciation base (49.8% YoY revenue growth in 2025), (b) per-satellite manufacturing and launch costs decline, and (c) the constellation reaches sufficient density that revenue per satellite exceeds depreciation per satellite. Viasat\'s negative operating income, despite a lower satellite-specific depreciation rate, shows that GEO operators face a different problem (sub-scale revenue relative to a lumpy, impairment-prone asset base).\n\n5. **Implication for peer benchmarking.** When evaluating LEO broadband operators (SpaceX/Starlink, potential peers such as Project Kuiper, OneWeb), investors should anchor on **operating income or free cash flow**, not EBITDA, because:\n   - EBITDA systematically overstates LEO profitability by ignoring perpetual replenishment capex;\n   - Useful-life assumptions — invisible in EBITDA — are the most material accounting estimate;\n   - The EBITDA-to-OI conversion ratio itself is a diagnostic: a low or negative conversion ratio signals that the operator has not yet achieved the scale or cost efficiency needed to cover its structural depreciation burden.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nSpaceX\'s Connectivity segment carries an implied D&A add-back of **$2,376 million** (20.87% of segment revenue) in its FY2025 EBITDA bridge, driven by 5-year satellite useful lives and continuous replenishment. Viasat\'s most recent 10-K does not separately disclose satellite depreciation, but total Communication Services depreciation is $988.4 million (29.97% of segment revenue), with estimated satellite-only depreciation of roughly $312 million (~9.46% of revenue) given 7–17 year GEO useful lives. The comparison confirms that **LEO satellite depreciation is structurally more intense per dollar of revenue than GEO satellite depreciation**, but SpaceX has achieved positive operating income (61.7% EBITDA conversion) through scale and cost efficiency, while Viasat\'s segment shows negative operating income despite positive EBITDA. This makes EBITDA-to-operating-income conversion the single most important diagnostic when evaluating LEO broadband operators, because the depreciation gap is permanent, useful-life-sensitive, and masks the perpetual capital intensity that defines the LEO business model.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Connectivity segment reconciliation, satellite useful-life disclosures, depreciation sensitivity"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/797721/000095017025077138/vsat-20250331.htm",\n      "name": "Viasat Inc. Form 10-K for fiscal year ended March 31, 2025 (filed May 27, 2025) — Communication Services segment depreciation, satellite useful lives, property and equipment note"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
