agnostic: a low or negative conversion ratio signals that the operator has not yet achieved the scale or cost efficiency needed to cover its structural depreciation burden.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nSpaceX\'s Connectivity segment carries an implied D&A add-back of **$2,376 million** (20.87% of segment revenue) in its FY2025 EBITDA bridge, driven by 5-year satellite useful lives and continuous replenishment. Viasat\'s most recent 10-K does not separately disclose satellite depreciation, but total Communication Services depreciation is $988.4 million (29.97% of segment revenue), with estimated satellite-only depreciation of roughly $312 million (~9.46% of revenue) given 7–17 year GEO useful lives. The comparison confirms that **LEO satellite depreciation is structurally more intense per dollar of revenue than GEO satellite depreciation**, but SpaceX has achieved positive operating income (61.7% EBITDA conversion) through scale and cost efficiency, while Viasat\'s segment shows negative operating income despite positive EBITDA. This makes EBITDA-to-operating-income conversion the single most important diagnostic when evaluating LEO broadband operators, because the depreciation gap is permanent, useful-life-sensitive, and masks the perpetual capital intensity that defines the LEO business model.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Connectivity segment reconciliation, satellite useful-life disclosures, depreciation sensitivity"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/797721/000095017025077138/vsat-20250331.htm",\n      "name": "Viasat Inc. Form 10-K for fiscal year ended March 31, 2025 (filed May 27, 2025) — Communication Services segment depreciation, satellite useful lives, property and equipment note"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
